Amdahl's Law demonstrates that the maximum speedup of a parallel application is fundamentally constrained by its serial (non-parallelizable) portion, setting a theoretical upper limit on scalability regardless of the number of processors added. It posits that as parallel resources increase, the execution time approaches the limit of the sequential part (






), meaning a small serial fraction acts as a dominant bottleneck that causes rapid diminishing returns, where adding more threads yields negligible performance gains once the parallelizable portion (
) is efficiently distributed. This reveals that designing parallel applications is not simply a matter of adding hardware, but requires rigorous, often complex, efforts to minimize serial dependencies—such as data synchronization, initialization, or I/O—to achieve true scalability, as even a 5% serial portion limits maximum speedup to 20x, regardless of whether 100 or 10,000 cores are used.
